===Etymology===
From {{etyl|enm}} {{term|wesele|lang=enm}}, from {{etyl|ang|en}} {{term|weosule||lang=ang}}, from {{etyl|gem-pro|en}} {{recons|wisulǭ|lang=gem-pro}} (compare {{etyl|fy|-}} {{term|wezeling||lang=fy}}, {{etyl|nl|-}} {{term|wezel||lang=nl}}, {{etyl|de|-}} {{term|Wiesel||lang=de}}), from {{etyl|ine-pro|en}} {{recons|wiselos|lang=ine-pro}} (compare [[Irish]] {{term|fíal|lang=ga}} 'ferret'), from *''wis''- 'musk, stink' (compare {{etyl|la|-}} {{term|virus|lang=la}} 'slimy liquid, mud; stench', {{etyl|sa|-}} {{term|विस्र|tr=visra|lang=sa}} 'musty, smelling of raw meat)'.

The verb comes from the supposed cunningness of the weasel.

